/*
 * SoC-side / PL device-tree fixups for VEK280, layered on top of the
 * gen-machineconf / lopper-generated <...>-linux.dts (which already carries
 * the PS config and the PL xilinx_qdma PCIe Root Ports from the XSA via
 * pl.dtsi). Scoped to the Linux domain by device-tree.bbappend.
 *
 * PCIe outbound-window fix (qdma_0 / qdma_1 `ranges`):
 *   The SDT/lopper-generated `ranges` set the PCI base address to 0x0 (i.e.
 *   PCI 0x0 -> CPU 0xa8000000), but the Versal QDMA bridge forwards CPU
 *   addresses 1:1 to the PCIe bus. With the mismatched ranges the kernel
 *   assigns endpoint BARs near PCI 0x0 while CPU accesses through the window
 *   land at PCI 0xa8000000 -> nothing responds -> AXI decode error surfaces
 *   as an Asynchronous SError and the kernel panics in nvme_pci_enable.
 *   PetaLinux's HSI-generated DT uses 1:1 ranges (PCI addr == CPU addr); we
 *   override to match. VEK280 is a dual-QDMA design and uses the same ranges
 *   as VCK190 (HW-validated there).
 *
 *   Format: <pci_addr(3 cells) cpu_addr(2 cells) size(2 cells)>; first entry
 *   is the 32-bit MEM window, second is the 64-bit (prefetchable) window.
 *
 * NOTE: the PetaLinux VEK280 system-user.dtsi also adds a reserved-memory
 * block (pl_ddr / lpddr_memory) and the zocl PL node. Those are not required
 * for PCIe/NVMe boot and the parse-sdt SDT already describes the board memory,
 * so they are intentionally omitted here. Re-add only if a workload needs the
 * PL-DDR/LPDDR carveout.
 */

&qdma_0 {
	ranges = <0x02000000 0x0 0xa8000000  0x0 0xa8000000  0x0 0x04000000>,
		 <0x43000000 0x4 0x80000000  0x4 0x80000000  0x0 0x40000000>;
};

&qdma_1 {
	ranges = <0x02000000 0x0 0xac000000  0x0 0xac000000  0x0 0x04000000>,
		 <0x43000000 0x4 0xc0000000  0x4 0xc0000000  0x0 0x40000000>;
};
